(61, '2017-10-20', 1, 'single', 'single', 'Team managed to operate successful rescue from Camp IV of Mt. Manaslu', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">October 20, 2017<img src=\"https://platform-cdn.sharethis.com/img/pinterest.svg\" alt=\"pinterest sharing button\" /></p>\r\n<div class=\"blog-entry\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Mingma Sherpa</strong>, Chairman at Seven Summit Treks, who had flown to Manalsu today morning with Two Sherpas; Sona and Dawa gyalje (also known as Ang Dawa) confirmed that the duo has been able to rescue a Sherpa Climber who fell ill on his way back from the summit. Lakpa Tsheri, who had been accompanying climber Nima Gyalzen Sherpa and a Chinese lady in their expedition to Mount Manasalu, had lost his ability to walk at Camp IV. Lakpa Tsheri, along with Nima Gyalzen and the Chinese citizen, has successfully scaled Mt. Manaslu, the mountain marked as the 8<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;Highest Peak in the World on the 19<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;of October.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This morning (9:00 AM- Local Time) the helicopter dropped two experienced Sherpas from Seven Summit Treks at Camp III (6,750m) of Mt. Manaslu. The team took 2 and half hours to reach from C3 to C4 (7,400m) and 3 more hours to bring down the injured climber to an access point from where the Heli flight could be operated.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">According to Mingma Sherpa, &ldquo;The rescued person has been admitted to Grande Hospital, Tokha, Kathmandu and is now safe. This rescue is one of the most dangerous rescues ever operated in my career. In a single day, we can perform such an incredible feat. We flew from Kathmandu to C4 (7,400m) of Manaslu and again back to Kathmandu.&rdquo; &ldquo;Our rescue team did an excellent job and was able to take the right action in time. We were able to bring the man down to safety at 4:20 PM.&rdquo; <strong>Chhang Dawa Sherpa</strong>, Director of SST added.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This autumn, different agencies had issued 255 individual permits to operate expeditions on Manaslu. The summit on 19 October by Lakpa Tsheri, Nima Gyalzen, and the Chinese citizen was the last summit of this Autumn.</p>\r\n</div>', '<p>Team managed to operate successful rescue from Camp IV of Mt. Manaslu</p>', 'team-managed-to-operate-successful-rescue-from-camp-iv-of-mt-manaslu', '1649340686166530872', 5, 0, 0, 2, '', 'thumbnail-1600x1200-r3niO0wFPRGHDcMlGw5C3Fzabuq7oFjFmhaXK3Fz.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '1', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'en', '2022-04-07 14:11:26', '2022-05-16 05:36:03'),
(62, '2018-01-20', 1, 'single', 'single', 'Winter Summit of Mt. Pumori - Alex and the team', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">January 20, 2018</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Today at 11:30 AM, the team of&nbsp;<strong>Alex Txikon (Spain)</strong>&nbsp;successfully climbed to the summit of Mt. Pumori situated at an altitude of 7,161m under the management of Seven Summit Treks. The team that includes&nbsp;<strong>Muhammad Ali Sadpara (Pakistan)</strong>, Nuri Sherpa, and Temba Bhote is now heading back to the base camp after the successful climb. The team aims to climb atop the summit of Mt. Everest this winter and has, so far, reached camp II on the way to Everest. They have ascended the peak as a part of their winter expedition and the final ascent of the summit will be completed by the third week of February. The first-ever successful winter expedition of Mt. Pumori was accomplished by two Japanese citizens named Hiroshi Aota and Yoshiki Sasahara in 1986.</p>', '<p>Winter Summit of Mt. Pumori - Alex and the team</p>', 'winter-summit-of-mt-pumori-alex-and-the-team', '1649340763349940321', 5, 0, 0, 3, '', 'thumbnail-1600x1200-0w3iYsKhyMfktYhYTL6x6g9lf3nByOeUs26omIku.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '1', '1', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'en', '2022-04-07 14:12:43', '2022-05-16 05:35:30'),
(63, '2018-04-05', 1, 'single', 'single', 'Man on the Everest, more than anyone in the planet', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">April 5, 2018</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Since the first ascent of Mt. Everest by Edmund Hillary and Tenzing Norgay on 29 May 1953 via S-Col SE Ridge approximately 5231 ascents are counted from the Nepal side till spring 2017 and &ldquo;Sherpa&rdquo; from the very first to now witnessed almost all attempts on the world&rsquo;s highest peak. Mt. Everest also known as Sagarmatha and Chomolungma is situated at an altitude of 8,848m (29,029 ft.) in the MahalungurHimal Range between the Nepal and China Border with the coordinates of 27&deg;59\'17\"N 86&deg;5\'31\"E.</p>\r\n<div class=\"blog-entry\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The highest peak of the world, Mt. Everest has been climbed multiple times by both Sherpas and foreigners, but remarkably only 3 individuals (all Sherpa) can script the history of Everest for 21 equal ascents. Apa Sherpa aka &lsquo;Super Sherpa&rsquo; from Thame, PhurbaTashi from Khumjung, and Kami Rita from Thame, all 3 have scaled the highest peak more than anyone on the planet. Apa Sherpa climbed Mt. Everest 21 times between 10 May 1990 &ndash; 11 May 2011, PhurbaTashi Sherpa between 27 May 1999 &ndash; 10 May 2013, and Kami Rita Sherpa between 13 May 1994 &ndash; 27 May 2017.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The 48-year-old Kami Rita inhabitant of Thame, Solukhumbu reached the highest point on 13 May 1994 as his first ascent of Everest and continued his high altitude journey by climbing Annapurna IV in 1996, Cho Oyu 8188m for 8 times from 2001 to 2011, Lhotse 8516m in 2011, Mt. K 2 (8611m) in 2014 Manaslu 8163 in 2017.</p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\" border=\"1\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.3078%; text-align: center;\" width=\"116\"><strong>S.N.</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 19.49%; text-align: center;\" width=\"163\"><strong