(481, '2 PEAKS [MERA + ISLAND] PEAK CLIMBING', '2 PEAKS [MERA + ISLAND] PEAK CLIMBING', '24 Days', '6,476M./21,247 FT.', 1, '4 - 6 Hours', '2-10 Pax', 'Hotel + Lodge + Tent', 'Via Amphu Laptse', NULL, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Mera + Island', 2, 'Khumbu Himal', NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, 'Mera + Island Peak Climbing', NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Mera Peak climbing and trekking, followed by a return journey via the Amphu Lapcha Pass and crossing Island Peak, offers a thrilling and immersive adventure in the heart of the Nepalese Himalayas.</p>', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Mera Peak</strong> elevates 6,476m above sea level in the Mahalangur section of the Himalayas, south of Mt. Everest. The journey begins with the ascent of Mera Peak, one of Nepal\'s highest trekking peaks standing at 6,476 meters. As climbers navigate through picturesque landscapes and diverse terrain, they are greeted with breathtaking views of towering peaks including Everest, Lhotse, Makalu, and Cho Oyu.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Mera Peak climb typically involves a gradual acclimatization process, allowing climbers to adjust to the altitude while soaking in the beauty of the surrounding wilderness. Trekkers traverse through dense forests, tranquil valleys, and high alpine meadows, encountering remote Sherpa villages along the way. Upon reaching the summit of Mera Peak, climbers are rewarded with unparalleled panoramic vistas, encompassing some of the world\'s most iconic peaks and vast glaciers. The sense of accomplishment and awe-inspiring scenery make the summit moment truly unforgettable.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Following the ascent of Mera Peak, the journey continues towards the challenging yet exhilarating crossing of the Amphu Lapcha Pass. Situated at an altitude of 5,845 meters, the pass presents climbers with technical challenges including steep ascents, icy slopes, and crevassed terrain. However, the effort is met with the unparalleled beauty of the surrounding landscape, as climbers traverse between towering peaks and vast glaciers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Descending from the Amphu Lapcha Pass, trekkers venture into the tranquil sanctuary of the Khumbu region, where they reconnect with familiar trails leading back toward Lukla. Along the way, the journey is punctuated by encounters with yaks, prayer wheels, and the warm hospitality of local teahouses.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>\" We await to serve you our service and share our experience with you \"</strong></p>', '', '3', NULL, 163, NULL, '2-peaks-mera-island-peak-climbing', 11, NULL, NULL, 'mera peak, island peak, 2 peaks climbing', NULL, 'mera-peak-zFmTfe5TtgcQYCdLhVkJG4qJ6CeToBx30cDtnfxF.jpg', '1717647187_mera-peak-fo1mGQmmWLj4vHisr3V3Owtk2iWe0DPQDOAO85Bh.jpg', 280, 0, '1', 0, '2024-06-06 03:46:40', '2024-09-25 07:29:53'),
(482, 'MT. VINSON (4892M) + SOUTH POLE - THE LAST DEGREE', 'Mt. Vinson (4892m) + South Pole - The Last Degree', '28 Days', '4892 M.', 3, NULL, '7 - 10 PAX', NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Mt. Vinson', 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-fareast-font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Mount Vinson is part of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains, the tallest peak in Antarctica, standing at 4,892 meters (16,050 feet) above sea level, located in western Antarctica overlooking the Ronne Ice Shelf. It is one of the latest additions to the list of the Seven Summits, representing the highest mountains on each of the seven continents. Indeed, fewer climbers have summited Mount Vinson than Mount Everest. This is largely because of its secluded position within the rugged Ellsworth Mountains, which rendered it nearly unreachable and a logistical challenge to climb until recent times.</span></p>', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Mount Vinson is part of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains, the tallest peak in Antarctica, standing at 4,892 meters (16,050 feet) above sea level, located in western Antarctica overlooking the Ronne Ice Shelf. It is one of the latest additions to the list of the Seven Summits, representing the highest mountains on each of the seven continents. Indeed, fewer climbers have summited Mount Vinson than Mount Everest. This is largely because of its secluded position within the rugged Ellsworth Mountains, which rendered it nearly unreachable and a logistical challenge to climb until recent times.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">An expedition to Vinson Peak is often referred to as the “Key to the Seven Summits.” While the mountain itself does not pose significant technical challenges, reaching it is extremely difficult due to two main factors: its extreme remoteness and the high cost of any expedition. Consequently, a journey to the Vinson Massif is uniquely interesting and prestigious, with very few people having accomplished it.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Our program begins in Punta Arenas, Chile. From there, we fly to Union Glacier in Antarctica. A smaller plane then transports us to the Vinson Massif Base Camp, where we set up our tents. After establishing Low Camp and High Camp, we proceed to the summit.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Mount Vinson and South Pole Expedition:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left: 22.5pt; text-indent: -0.25in; text-align: justify;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">§<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">  </span></span></span><!--[endif]--> <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Activities:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\"> Mountaineering and skiing.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 22.5pt; text-indent: -0.25in; text-align: justify;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">§<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">  </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Mount Vinson:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\"> The climbing and skiing expedition begins at Punta Arenas, with flights to Union Glacier and then to Vinson Base Camp. Set up Low and High Camps before summiting.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 22.5pt; text-indent: -0.25in; text-align: justify;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span style=\"font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">§<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">  </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">South Pole:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\"> Fly from Union Glacier to the South Pole, explore and ski around the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station, experiencing the unique polar environment before returning to Union Glacier and Punta Arenas.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-fareast-font-family: Calibri; mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-font-width: 101%; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">This combined expedition to Mount Vinson and the South Pole offers a prestigious adventure, with mountaineering and skiing activities, making it a remarkable and rare achievement.</span></p>', '', '', NULL, 11, NULL, 'mt-vinson-4892m-south-pole-the-last-degree', 2, NULL, NULL, 'mt. vinson, Antarctica', NULL, 'vinson-dqOsOBBeXKWzAgIcqJOcxo0e0qgfsdl89mjGrtsG.jpg', '1723442636_vinson-JuBNrvLMFXa83gdNukegi8AKPsWgK5JbKNgKwLY2.jpg', 161, 0, '1', 0, '2024-08-12 04:39:06', '2024-09-25 07:21:03'),
(483, 'MT. VINSON EXPEDITION (4892M)', 'Mt. Vinson Expedition (4892m)', '16 Days', '4892 m.', 3, NULL, '7 - 10 PAX', NULL, NULL, NULL, 5, NULL, NULL, 'Mt. Vinson', 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\', sans-serif;\">Mount Vinson is a part of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains, the tallest peak in Antarctica, stands at 4,892 meters (16,050 feet) above sea level located in western Antarctica overlooking the Ronne Ice Shelf. It is one of the latest additions to the list of the Seven Summits, representing the highest mountains on each of the seven continents. Indeed, fewer climbers have summited Mount Vinson than Mount Everest. This is largely because of its secluded position within the rugged Ellsworth Mountains, which rendered it nearly unreachable and a logistical challenge to climb until recent times.</span></p>', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Mount Vinson is a part of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains, the tallest peak in Antarctica, stands at 4,892 meters (16,050 feet) above sea level located in western Antarctica overlooking the Ronne Ice Shelf. It is one of the latest additions to the list of the Seven Summits, representing the highest mountains on each of the seven continents. Indeed, fewer climbers have summited Mount Vinson than Mount Everest. This is largely because of its secluded position within the rugged Ellsworth Mountains, which rendered it nearly unreachable and a logistical challenge to climb until recent times.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">An expedition to Vinson Peak is often referred to as the “Key to the Seven Summits.” While the mountain itself does not pose significant technical challenges, reaching it is extremely difficult due to two main factors: its extreme remoteness and the high cost of any expedition. Consequently, a journey to the Vinson Massif is uniquely interesting and prestigious, with very few people having accomplished it.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin;\">Our program begins in Punta Arenas, Chile. From there, we fly to Patriot Hills in Antarctica, an airstrip owned by Chile and leased by Americans for tourist flights. A smaller plane then transports us to the Vinson Massif Base Camp, where we set up our tents. After establishing Low Camp and High Camp, we proceed to the summit.</span></strong></p>', '', '', NULL, 11, NULL, 'mt-vinson-expedition-4892m', 3, NULL, NULL, 'mt. vinson, Antarctica', NULL, 'vinson-7453xpKVhIEcsRPDSeNuhhfnINS4BEjjGbOxExQm.jpg', '1723445528_vinson-jzZsM9dbRQThPx05jzJUvkTYfneonWkOjcOqu2Vu.jpg', 141, 0, '1', 0, '2024-08-12 06:49:03', '2024-09-25 07:32:03');
