(35, 1, NULL, 'Instruction for Summit Bonus, Tips and Hidden Cost', 'Instruction for Summit Bonus, Tips and Hidden Cost', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin; color: black; mso-color-alt: windowtext; background: white;\">SUMMIT BONUS:</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin; color: black; mso-color-alt: windowtext; background: white;\">  </span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Calibri Light\',sans-serif; mso-ascii-theme-font: major-latin; mso-hansi-theme-font: major-latin; mso-bidi-theme-font: major-latin; color: black; mso-color-alt: windowtext; background: white;\">In the mountaineering culture of Nepal, China, and Pakistan a \"SUMMIT BONUS\" refers to an additional financial reward given to a Sherpa (high-altitude climbing guide) upon successfully reaching a mountain\'s summit or assisting members during the expedition period. This incentive, paid by the expedition members, aims to motivate Sherpas, recognize their significant efforts, and acknowledge the physical, mental, and logistical challenges involved. It is particularly common in high-altitude expeditions, such as those to Mt. Everest, and can vary in amount based on the mountain, organization, and climbers\' roles. This amount is an understanding between the client and the Sherpa; the expedition organizer or agency has nothing to do with it. However, the summit bonus is a mandatory payment that Sherpas expect and calculate in their overall income.</span></p>\r\n<table class=\"MsoTableGrid\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border: none; mso-border-alt: sol